<DATE>941209
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  09 DEC 94 / International Company News: SGS-Thomson steps into private
arena - The flotation paves the way for further injections
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN RIDDING and ANDREW HILL
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SGS-Thomson, the Franco- Italian semiconductor manufacturer, yesterday
launched an offer of up to 19 per cent of its shares on the New York and
Paris stock markets, and took its first step out of state ownership.
It seems a far cry from 1987 when two state-owned companies - Thomson
Semiconductors of France and SGS Microelectronics of Italy - decided to pool
their resources in an attempt to fight back against US and Japanese
competition, and pull themselves out of a trough of financial problems and
declining market share. At the time, the challenge of making the joint
venture work seemed a particularly tough one. As one analyst puts it: 'If
you can't turn a semiconductor company round in five years, you're lost.'
However, seven years on, SGS-Thomson is nearing the top 10 in the
semiconductor sector.
Mr Bill McClean, vice-president of Integrated Circuit Engineering, the
Arizona-based industry research and consultancy group, forecasts sales
growth of about 30 per cent this year - from Dollars 2.04bn in 1993 - which
makes the company the 11th or 12th biggest company in the industry. 'They
are definitely regarded as a serious competitor by the dominant US and
Japanese groups,' according to Mr McClean.
Helped by the recent upswing in the cyclical semiconductor industry,
SGS-Thomson has seen profits jump to Dollars 253.3m for the first nine
months of this year, nearly double the figure for the same period in 1993.
Investment in new plant and fast-growing technologies, diversity of products
and geographical spread have improved the group's medium-term prospects.
For example, SGS-Thomson produces mixed signal devices - which combine
analog and digital systems and whose uses range from cars to telecoms -
Eproms and Flash memories. The company is the world's biggest producer of
Eproms, non-volatile semiconductors in which memory is retained once the
power source has been removed, and has pushed ahead with the development of
the next generation Flash products, helped by its pre-eminence in Eproms.
The group is taking an aggressive step in the microprocessor market.
In April, it announced it was collaborating with Cyrix of the US to produce
microprocessors. The project faces potential legal hurdles because of court
battles between Cyrix and Intel, the dominant microprocessor manufacturer,
which is seeking to protect its patent rights.
However, most observers believe it is a significant strategic move for
SGS-Thomson. 'They have the capacity in place at their Phoenix plant and
they should be up and running pretty quickly,' says one Paris-based analyst.
'This is critical because the timing will be vital in winning market share.'
As for geographical spread, 'unlike Phillips and Siemens, which are still
fairly reliant on Europe, they have a pretty well-balanced exposure,' says
one electronics analyst at a French merchant bank.
Like its European counterparts SGS-Thomson still faces a problem of size. Mr
Mike Glennon, semiconductor analyst at Dataquest, the UK technology research
consultancy, says there are three fundamental elements to success in the
microprocessor market: produce an industry-standard product; sort out patent
issues with Intel; and make sure you have the ability to produce to meet
market demand. 'You need to be able to invest millions of dollars because
manufacturing plant costs in the region of Dollars 1bn,' he says. 'The 'in
between' position is going to be tough,' adds Mr McClean, who believes
SGS-Thomson needs to 'get big, and keep rolling'.
Mr Pasquale Pistorio, the company's Italian chairman, sketches a scenario in
which the financial and technological requirements of the sector will divide
it into two broad categories - general, broad-range semiconductor suppliers
and small specialist producers. The dividing line, he believes, will be
determined by market share and the crucial level will be about 5 per cent, a
few points higher than his company's present slice of the market.
To lift the company out of what he describes as 'the grey zone', Mr Pistorio
has pursued a policy of expansion. This has meant strengthening the group's
capital base. Last year, SGS-Thomson received two capital injections of each
from its state shareholders, reducing debts to about Dollars 275.5m at the
beginning of this year, compared with a peak of about Dollars 904m at the
end of 1991.
Such financing has prompted criticism from US rivals, who oppose the state
financing of their European competitor, but it is no longer an option
because of budget pressures on both the Italian and French governments.
Hence the move to the market. The initial offering of shares - 16.3 per cent
of the total number - should net receipts of about Dollars 470m. More
importantly, it prepares the path for further capital injections from
private shareholders and an eventual move from public sector control.
The French industry ministry describes such a scenario as premature.
However, the Italian and French governments are both enacting an ambitious
programme of privatisation aimed at easing the financial burden of the
state's involvement in industry.
In many cases flotation is followed by privatisation. The capital
requirements of SGS-Thomson and the industry in which it is competing,
suggest it may follow a similar course.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Companies:-
</XX>
<CO>SGS-Thomson Microelectronics.
</CO>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>FRZ  France, EC.
    USZ  United States of America.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P3674 Semiconductors and Related Devices.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>CMMT  Comment &amp; Analysis.
    FIN  Share issues.
</TP>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
