<HEADLINE>
FT  09 DEC 94 / International Company News: Nat Semi ahead in quarter
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By Agencies and REUTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   HILLSBORO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
National Semiconductor, the US chip maker, yesterday reported improved
second-quarter net income, up at Dollars 67m from Dollars 60m on sales up
slightly to Dollars 584m from Dollars 582m, Agencies report.
For the half year, net climbed to Dollars 126m from Dollars 117m, which
included a gain of Dollars 4.9m for the cumulative effect of an accounting
change. Half-year sales were virtually flat.
National Semiconductor said: 'New order rates are up 20 per cent to 25 per
cent over last year, led by the analog and mixed signal product lines that
support our moving and shaping markets.'
The company said analog and mixed signal products represented 56 per cent of
total sales in the second quarter, compared with 52 per cent a year ago, and
orders for analog and mixed signal devices were up more than 35 per cent.
The company also said its power management segment led bookings growth with
additional strength shown by our Super I/O and local area network product
lines.
National Semiconductor said: 'Orders improved throughout the (latest)
quarter, with November showing strong results.'
Intel, the leading US microprocessor manufacturer, has announced plans to
build a new chip manufacturing and development plant in Hillsboro, Oregon,
spending Dollars 565m on the first phase, Reuter reports from Hillsboro.
That phase, to begin immediately, will include a 500,000 sq ft wafer
fabrication facility, and office and support buildings. Intel expects
completion by 1997.
</TEXT>
