FT  09 DEC 94 / International Company News: Cost cuts at Lufthansa paying
off
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By AP-DJ
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   FRANKFURT
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Lufthansa, the German airline, is on course to post a parent-company pre-tax
profit for the fourth quarter and resume paying dividends for the full year,
AP-DJ reports from Frankfurt. It also said it was taking a stake in a
Frankfurt-based travel company.
The airline confirmed parent-company nine-month pre-tax profit of DM325m
(Dollars 207m). Lufthansa does not publish group figures on a quarterly
basis.
In November, it predicted it would post a profit for the full year and
resume the payout.
The airline said a report given by Mr Jurgen Weber, management board
chairman, at the final meeting of its supervisory board showed that
Lufthansa's cost-cutting measures, begun 10 months ago, had continued to be
successful.
It also said it planned to take a 25 per cent stake in Alpha Holding tourism
company, as well as an option to buy a further 5 per cent. The move is aimed
at strengthening the tourism business of Lufthansa's Condor charter unit.
Alpha Holding includes the wholly-owned unit Air Marin Flugreisen, which
organises trips. Alpha Reisebueros, the travel bureau chain, also belongs to
the holding group.
