FT  09 DEC 94 / International Company News: Lukoil unveils scheme to attract
foreign investors
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT CORZINE and CHRYSTIA FREELAND
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Lukoil, Russia's largest oil company and one of its most
commercially-oriented organisations, yesterday unveiled its strategy to
attract between Dollars 3bn and Dollars 7bn in foreign investment over the
next few years.
Mr Vagit Alekperov, Lukoil president, said he hoped the flotation of as much
as 15 per cent of Lukoil shares to foreign investors would be completed in
1996.
He was speaking yesterday in London, where senior Lukoil officials met City
financial institutions and other potential investors. Earlier this week, the
Russian executives made a similar presentation to US investors in New York.
Some Lukoil shares are already held by foreigners, including a 3.5 per cent
stake by Credit Suisse First Boston. However, substantial work has yet to be
done on valuing the company's assets and presenting the information in an
internationally-recognised format before it can expand its foreign ownership
base.
KPMG, the international accounting firm, and McKinsey, the consulting group,
are working with the company, as are several western banks seeking to take
part in the tender offer. The company has not, however, chosen an
international market on which to list its shares.
Mr Alekperov said Lukoil, whose fields in western Siberia produce a sixth of
Russia's oil, intended to enhance its attractiveness to investors over the
next year through internal restructuring and further acquisitions.
The company will take full control of its biggest producing subsidiaries in
1995. It also plans to acquire at least five additional companies.
Lukoil has begun to transfer some of its social responsibilities, such as
housing, to local governments in the areas in which it operates. It also
wants to shed some of its extensive ancillary services, such as running
railways to transport oil.
'If we can get better services more cheaply, then we will divest
immediately,' Mr Alekperov said.
Lukoil's long-term strategic goal was to become a fully private company, he
said. However, the Russian government, with which Lukoil has close links,
still has a 45 per cent shareholding.
Mr Alekperov held out the prospect of additional tranches of shares being
offered to foreign investors to fund specific projects.
'Our first priority is to broaden our sphere of activity in Russia,' he
said. Another priority for Mr Alekperov, who is from Azerbaijan, was
participation in oil development projects in the Caspian Sea region.
Lukoil has a 10 per cent share in a British Petroleum-led consortium to
develop three offshore fields in Azerbaijan. Mr Alekperov said Lukoil also
wanted to take part in large oil developments in all the other countries
bordering the Caspian.
Mr Alekperov expressed confidence that a new oil and gas law governing
production-sharing contracts and joint ventures in Russia would soon be
passed by parliament.
</TEXT>
