<HEADLINE>
FT  09 DEC 94 / UK Company News: Institutions contribute to MPE fund-raising
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD GOURLAY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Montagu Private Equity has raised Pounds 170m from four UK and continental
European institutions and Pounds 250m from HSBC Group, its parent, for
investment in unquoted companies.
Montagu intends to raise Pounds 500m in what it is calling a Private Equity
Partnership Scheme. HSBC is committed to invest at least as much as each
co-investor in every deal.
This is the first time that Montagu Private Equity (MPE) has raised this
amount of capital from institutions other than its parent and signals HSBC's
intention to increase its presence in private equity investment.
The move confirms MPE as one of the UK's three largest providers of private
equity capital.
The new funds will add to the weight of new money raised by UK venture
capital and management buy-out financiers recently. The British Venture
Capital Association says that in the eight months to August, UK fund
managers have raised over Pounds 2bn - more than three times as much as in
the whole of 1993.
MPE's investors committed the funds for five years, but Mr Ian Forrest, its
managing director, said he hoped to develop a long-term investment
partnership with this small number of investors.
Mr Forrest said these institutions had not been significant investors in
private equity before.
MPE has invested about Pounds 100m a year recently and intends to continue
to invest at a similar rate. 'We are saying we have a lot of money for this
class of asset and the ability to be a long term partner (with businesses),'
Mr Forrest said. 'HSBC is saying this is a core businesses for investment
banking.'
The fund raising not only increased MPE's management fees, but also provided
the firepower to underwrite the total equity requirement of any transaction.
</TEXT>
