<HEADLINE>
FT  09 DEC 94 / GUS gives Pounds 300m back to shareholders in special
dividend
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NEIL BUCKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Great Universal Stores, the mail order, retail, property and financial
services group, is to hand Pounds 300m of its Pounds 1.5bn cash pile back to
shareholders in the form of a 30p per share special dividend.
The proposed dividend was announced as the group revealed a 5.5 per cent
increase in pre-tax profits for the six months to September 30, from Pounds
213.2m to Pounds 225m.
But with the special dividend payable only to those holding shares
yesterday, and the smaller than expected profits - GUS shares fell 35p to
496p.
Mr Richard Pugh, deputy chairman, said the group had been seeking ways of
redistributing some of its cash for some time. It decided a special dividend
was the 'most equitable' way of giving money back to shareholders, but had
to stay 'within certain parameters' to gain approval from the Inland
Revenue.
The move by GUS last year to enfranchise its non-voting shareholders sparked
hopes in the City of a change of culture in one of the more conservative and
low-profile FT-SE 100 companies.
Speculation that GUS might launch a share buy-back resurfaced following the
Pounds 508m buy-back by fellow retailer Boots last month, and some analysts
were disappointed that GUS instead chose a special dividend.
Other analysts were disappointed by the size of the payout and suggested GUS
might pay further special dividends in future.
Mr Pugh said the group would continue to look for appropriate ways of using
its cash. It was still seeking an acquisition 'which complements our
existing business and has a good, continuing management'.
He added that GUS was ready to use its strength in mail order to launch
electronic shopping services, once the infrastructure - national fibre-optic
cabling - was in place, and consumer demand was strong enough.
'We have got the systems ready, they have been tried and tested, but the
public demand is not there yet,' Mr Pugh said.
Group turnover rose from Pounds 1.39bn to Pounds 1.54bn. The trading profit
increased 11.2 per cent to Pounds 176.7m, although interest receivable fell
from Pounds 51.6m to Pounds 46.3m.
Sales in the home shopping division, which includes the Kays and Marshall
Ward catalogues, increased 6 per cent to Pounds 868.1m. Operating profits
grew 13 per cent to Pounds 77.5m, thanks to cost control.
Sales in the Burberrys and Scotch House clothing and retailing division grew
from Pounds 85.4m to Pounds 102.2m. The overseas retailing division
increased sales 9 per cent to Pounds 96.5m, and operating profits from
Pounds 11m to Pounds 11.8m. Profits from property rentals grew from Pounds
26.8m to Pounds 29.4m.
Turnover in the finance division, which includes consumer and corporate
finance, banking and business information services, jumped from Pounds 398m
to Pounds 472.5m, with profits up from Pounds 36.5m to Pounds 40.4m.
The interim dividend, which will be paid together with the special dividend,
rose from 4p to 4.5p. Earnings per share rose from 14.1p to 14.8p.
Lex, Page 18
</TEXT>
