<HEADLINE>
FT  09 DEC 94 / Allianz plans to make its shares more affordable
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW FISHER and RALPH ATKINS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MUNICH
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Allianz, Germany's biggest insurance group, wants to make its costly shares
more attractive to small investors by cutting their nominal value and thus
splitting them into smaller units, according to Mr Henning Schulte-Noelle,
the chairman.
His statement, in an interview with the Financial Times, comes in the same
week that Dresdner Bank became the first big German concern to announce firm
plans to reduce the nominal value of its stock units from DM50 to DM5. This
is allowed under new legislation to promote the attractiveness and
efficiency of German financial markets.
'If we can make sure that trading in our shares is made easier, then of
course we are interested in this whole development,' Mr Schulte-Noelle said.
However, because of technical procedures over the handling of its shares
(registered under individual names rather than in more easily processed
bearer form) and the costs of moving to lower-denominated shares, he said
this may take two years.
With a closing price yesterday of DM2,466 (Pounds 1,006), Allianz's shares
are among the most expensive in Germany. Dresdner's were DM408.50 and those
of Deutsche Bank, also considering such a move, were DM729.
Mr Schulte-Noelle said smaller denominated shares could play a role in
encouraging German investors to invest more in equities.
'For small investors, it makes a difference whether they have to pay around
DM2,500 for one Allianz share or DM250.' Allianz shares are among the most
heavily traded on the Frankfurt stock exchange.
Many big foreign investors see them as a proxy for the whole German market
because Allianz has extensive stakes in companies and banks as part of its
investment portfolio, earnings on which offset losses on insurance
underwriting. Thus Mr Schulte-Noelle expressed strong concern over political
moves in Bonn to restrict industrial holdings of banks and maybe other
financial institutions.
'This is a debate we follow very, very carefully because it could possibly
affect us in various ways.' If shareholdings were limited to, say 5 per
cent, 'this would have a great effect on our industrial investments.'
Companies in which Allianz has minority stakes above 10 per cent include
BASF, Bayerische Hypo-Bank, Dresdner Bank, BHF-Bank, Munich Re, Veba and
RWE.
In turn, 60 per cent of its equity is owned by Munich Re (with 25 per cent),
Deutsche Bank, Bayerische Vereinsbank and Dresdner Bank with 10 per cent
each, and Hypo-Bank with 5 per cent.
Mr Schulte-Noelle said action to curb financial stakes in industry would put
a 'tremendous burden' on the stock market. 'It would drive prices down and
that cannot be in the interests of the government.'
He also opposed moves to limit further the number of seats anyone may hold
on a company's supervisory board. 'We are big investors and if we own maybe
10 per cent of a big company, we have a definite interest in sitting on the
supervisory board to see what's happening.'
Finanzplatz Frankfurt, Page 16
</TEXT>
