<HEADLINE>
FT  09 DEC 94 / Mitsubishi breaks ranks to buy steel from S Korea
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHIYO NAKAMOTO
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TOKYO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
A significant crack has appeared in Japan's traditional corporate
relationships with the unprecedented decision by Mitsubishi Motors to import
steel from South Korea, long seen by Japanese manufacturers as their chief
rival.
Mitsubishi Motors, the carmaker within the Mitsubishi group of companies,
broke an industry taboo by signing a contract with Korea's Pohang Iron and
Steel to buy steel sheet on a long-term basis.
The agreement reflects growing pressures on Japanese manufacturers to lower
costs following the yen's appreciation. The Organisation for Economic
Co-operation and Development, in its annual survey of Japan's economy,
warned yesterday that the yen's strength was the biggest threat to the
country's emerging recovery.
Mitsubishi would not disclose the price of Korean steel sheet, but it is
believed to be 15 to 20 per cent cheaper than the Japanese product. Nissan,
Japan's second largest carmaker, and Honda also said they were testing
Korean steel sheet.
Reports of the Korean imports, decided on Wednesday, depressed the share
prices of Japanese steel companies on the Tokyo Stock Exchange. Nippon
Steel, the world's largest steelmaker, was the most actively traded issue,
down Y6 to Y368 (Dollars 3.7). NKK and Kobe Steel were also among the 10
most actively traded issues, with NKK down Y9 to Y269 and Kobe down Y5 to
Y311.
Strong yen biggest risk for Japan, Page 4
Tokyo stocks, Page 37
