<HEADLINE>
FT  09 DEC 94 / Observer: We presume
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Well, what indeed should be the moniker attaching to this impending grand
union? Image consultants get paid hundreds of thousands of dollars for this
sort of thing, but here is Observer's first try, gratis.
The most obvious, Morgan Warburg, has to be ditched right away - too close
to Deutsche Bank-owned Morgan Grenfell. Warburg would want a sharper
distinction from its old rival - even if a degree of fellow feeling might be
kindled between proud Brits forced to fall back on foreigners' superior
resources.
Warburg Morgan or Warburg Morgan Stanley is a non-starter, seeing that the
Americans will constitute two-thirds of the new company. Stanley Warburg, on
the other hand, is worse - sounds like a long-lost relative of old Sir
Siegmund's.
All of which suggests that the pair will wind up with the most obvious:
Morgan Stanley Warburg. A bit of a mouthful, but not so dreadful in a
business which has suffered handles such as Merrill Lynch Pierce Fenner &amp;
Smith.
</TEXT>
