<HEADLINE>
FT  09 DEC 94 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MARTIN HOYLE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
If you thought such traditional English characteristics as irony, fairness,
a vague but nagging sense of decency and (for better or worse) a love of
animals were vanishing, Short Stories: Pet Patients (8pm, Channel 4) should
reassure you of their survival.
I am unsure whether the Barleycorn family are real or intended as a pilot
for a future sitcom. Their south London council flat is a haven for dogs,
cats, rodents, reptiles and two pigs. This is deliberate. They like it. They
love it.
So do the devoted workers of the local Blue Cross animal hospital. It throws
up as much drama, comedy, tear-jerking and social issues as Casualty.
Maurice Melzac's film is quirky, original, sharp-eyed and unsentimental
about its dramatis personae, however many legs they have.
How different from the callous inhabitants of Chicago who flush unwanted
pets down the loo. Alligator (11.35pm, BBC1) makes an entertaining pendant
to the above; a 1980 feature film with a third-league cast but something of
a cult for post-closing time viewing.
</TEXT>
