<HEADLINE>
FT  09 DEC 94 / Budget Statement: Revenue raising wins approval - City
reaction
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP COGGAN, Economics Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The City took the chancellor's package in its stride, with analysts saying
the measures were roughly in line with expectations.
Economists were pleased that Mr Kenneth Clarke had announced revenue-raising
measures, rather than making adjustments to public spending targets, which
might not then be achieved.
Mr David Owen, UK economist at Kleinwort Benson, said 'we were concerned
that he was going to announce further cuts in the (public spending) control
total', which might have been simply due to a reduction in the contingency
reserve. Mr Bill Martin, chief economist of UBS in London, said the fact
that Mr Clarke 'didn't use smoke and mirrors will be taken very well'.
Mr Adam Cole, UK economist at James Capel, said the chancellor 'needed to do
something which gave a rap on the knuckles to the rebellious backbenchers by
imposing small but unpopular tax increases. He can lay the blame for the tax
rises fairly and squarely with the rebels'.
Most analysts were also encouraged by the reduction in future inflation
which would result from the package. The Treasury said that, had the rise in
VAT on domestic fuel and power gone ahead, it would have added 0.43 per cent
to the retail prices index in April. The new package will add 0.26 per cent
to the RPI from January, accordingly lowering the rate of inflation later in
the year by about 0.2 of a percentage point.
But Mr Ian Shepherdson, UK economist at HSBC Markets, was disappointed with
the package. 'The chancellor had a golden opportunity to deal with the RPI,'
he said, adding that a change in indirect taxes would have saved the full
0.4 per cent.
Mr Shepherdson said: 'When inflation is around 2 per cent, 0.4 of a point is
a hell of a lot.' A lower RPI would have reduced the pressure for higher pay
increases, he added.
Mr Shepherdson also pointed out that, by delaying the changes, the RPI
impact would not come through in the December inflation figure, which was
often used as a guide for January pay settlements.
Furthermore, the drinks industry might not pass on the full impact of the
excise duty increase to consumers. Mr Shepherdson said: 'Even at current
duty levels, cross-Channel shopping is crippling the off-sales trade in the
south-east.'
Poor households will be the biggest percentage winners from the government's
tax-raising switch, according to the Institute for Fiscal Studies.
The institute said the poorest 10 per cent of the population would gain 0.58
per cent of their net income, as a result of the replacement of the 17.5 per
cent band of value added tax on fuel with higher duties on alcohol, tobacco
and petrol.
The richest 10 per cent of the population gained only 0.11 per cent. The
institute said the progressive nature of the change was due to 'the removal
of a tax that bore very heavily on the poor, and its replacement by taxes
that are spread more evenly across the population'.
However, the institute said pensioners gained, on average, less than the
overall population.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
