<HEADLINE>
FT  09 DEC 94 / Budget Statement: Rumbustious style that cannot disguise
harsh reality - Philip Stephens considers whether the chancellor has been
weakened in the past days
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP STEPHENS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Kenneth Clarke has lived at the Commons despatch box these past 10 days.
It was the chancellor who opened the fateful debate on European Union
finances which tore open the party's wounds over Europe. Then the Budget.
Then a vain attempt to rescue the proposed increase in value added tax on
domestic fuel.
Finally yesterday came the 'mini-Budget' - or as he preferred to describe
it, the 'corrigendum' - to plug the financial gap left by the government's
worst parliamentary defeat since 1979.
On each occasion Mr John Major had sat by his side - most of the time
passive, sometimes scowling, occasionally chuckling, but always wondering
whether Mr Clarke's combative self-confidence was helping or hindering his
government's attempts to climb out from an ever deeper political hole.
Behind the two men, Tory MPs on the restless, rebellious back benches have
looked on with mixed emotions.
Many have contrasted the chancellor's rumbustious dismissal of the
government's calamities with the tired demeanour of the prime minister.
Journalists in the Commons press gallery have nodded assent as Mr Clarke has
soaked up the political punches from the opposition and Tory rebels alike.
Ken, after all, is an insider's politician, relaxed, witty and never lost
for a riposte at the despatch box.
But the admiration has not been universal. Others in his party judge that Mr
Clarke has been seriously damaged these past few days.
Politics is often as much about perceptions as about reality, he declared
during one of this week's Commons performances. But the chancellor cannot
disguise the reality that he is the first holder of the post to lose an
important tax measure since Mr Denis Healey in the chaotic final days of the
last Labour government. Nor can he hope that yesterday's package of tax
increases to fill the financial gap will be popular either in the country or
with his critics on the Tory right.
Some of his friends blame the party whips. They miscalculated, the argument
runs, the extent of opposition from the nine Eurosceptic rebels exiled from
the parliamentary party last week.
But Mr Clarke too failed to appreciate the anger in the country at the
imposition of higher-rate VAT on fuel - an anger which emboldened usually
loyal Tory MPs to join the irreconcilables in the revolt.
Then there is Europe. The original idea to make the vote on higher
contributions to the EU budget a life-or-death affair for the government
came from Mr Douglas Hurd, foreign secretary. But Mr Clarke, a fervent
pro-European, needed no convincing.
Impatient at the appeasement of the sceptics during the battle over
Maastricht, the chancellor is said to have assured rightwing cabinet
colleagues that only one or two would defy the government in a vote of
confidence. In the end nine lost the party whip, leaving Mr Major heading,
technically at least, a minority government.
Some on the Eurosceptic right of the Tory party see, as in most things, a
dark conspiracy in all this. The chancellor, after all, wears his
pro-Europeanism on his sleeve. He is the only senior member of the cabinet
willing to admit he favours a single European currency. Somehow Mr Clarke
has calculated that however damaged he is, Mr Major will fare worse. With
the prime minister's leadership under threat again, the chancellor can
demonstrate that he is made of sterner stuff.
Not so. Mr Clarke has been true to his political instincts. He is not, as an
old friend in the cabinet puts it, a man for measured argument. His
pugnacious style is frequently a strength. But the delight he takes in
antagonising opponents - the sceptics on the Tory back benches were brushed
aside yesterday as mere Euro-rebels and Mr Gordon Brown, his Labour shadow,
dismissed as infantile - is sometimes a weakness.
Mr Clarke's relationship with the prime minister is good, though neither
would describe it as warm. The chancellor consulted closely with Mr Major on
the Budget but made it clear that he was the one running the Treasury.
He would jump at the chance of the leadership if Mr Major fell but he is not
plotting his removal. Mr Clarke judges that his best chance of the
succession lies beyond rather than before the next election.
He thinks the prime minister is determined to fight that election. He sees a
common interest in the government winning. Then Mr Major probably would step
down. As the man who delivered the economic recovery, Mr Clarke would be the
front-runner to take over.
Maybe. The assumption that the Conservatives still have a reasonable chance
of winning the next election looks more heroic by the day. Mr Clarke's own
prospects also look more uncertain.
Income tax cuts before the election will repair easily the damage of the VAT
debacle. But the chancellor's contemptuous dismissal of his party's growing
band of Eurosceptics has narrowed his support among the electorate which
will chose the next Tory leader. He is still favourite but he needs to start
winning friends as well as kicking enemies.
</TEXT>
<XX>
