<HEADLINE>
FT  09 DEC 94 / Banks get guidelines on marketing of mortgages
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A voluntary code of practice on the information banks should give customers
choosing mortgages was launched yesterday by the British Bankers'
Association.
It has not, however, headed off demands for new regulation of the sale and
marketing of home loans.
The code was agreed in discussion between the bigger high street banks. They
said they already met its terms.
The Office of Fair Trading welcomed the guidance as 'a step forward but not
the end of the road'. In February, Sir Bryan Carsberg, director-general of
fair trading, called for lenders to be required to give borrowers the most
appropriate advice.
The guidance is more limited than the plans for a code being discussed by
the Council of Mortgage Lenders, which represents banks, building societies
and centralised lenders which sell through intermediaries rather than branch
networks.
The CML code is likely to include telling the borrower in writing after the
sale the reason why a particular type of mortgage was recommended as
appropriate.
Mortgages involving investments - such as endowments - will be included in
new financial services regulations next year which require more information
to be given to customers.
The annual report of the banking ombudsman, published earlier this week,
said requiring banks to give 'best advice' on mortgages would make
complaints about mortgages - the third biggest category of complaint - much
easier to deal with.
It also highlighted the difficulty of resolving mortgage complaints on the
basis of what the bank said when the loan was taken out, as this was usually
several years before the complaint.
</TEXT>
