<HEADLINE>
FT  09 DEC 94 / Grim outlook for Tories in Black Country
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BLITZ and PAUL CHEESERIGHT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
It looks bad for the Tories. Very bad. With less than a week to go to the
Dudley West by-election, there are signs that it might even be disastrous.
After a week like the one Mr John Major's government has just been through,
few people expect the Conservatives to hold on to this quiet constituency in
the heart of the Black Country.
On paper, it ought to be a tough task for Labour. The seat is number 101 on
its list of Tory targets. It has been held by the Conservatives break since
1979. And its local population is made up of the kind of hardened middle
class voters who epitomise rank-and-file Conservative supporters.
But few Tory candidates can ever have fought a by-election in conditions as
unfavourable as those facing Mr Graham Postles, a 37-year-old insurance
executive who lives in the area.
His party is now a record 39.5 points behind Labour in national opinion
polls. Its divisions have been fully exposed in debates on Europe and value
added tax in the Commons throughout the by-election campaign. And there is
no powerful Liberal Democrat challenge here threatening to split Labour's
vote.
Above all, the majority of 5,789 which Mr Postles is defending seems
trifling compared with the hefty Tory leads overturned at Christchurch and
Eastleigh in the past 18 months.
A senior Tory party official admitted this week that Labour should get a
majority of 6,000 next Thursday. But his demeanour let slip that even this
might be an underestimate. 'It's just been too difficult on the doorstep,'
he said.
A government minister who had campaigned in the constituency also admitted
at Westminster yesterday that the result could be disastrous.
At first glance the constituency of 80,000 electors occupies the kind of
industrial landscape which evokes the recent recession and discontent with
the Conservative administration.
Manufacturing in the Black Country is a shadow of its former self. Much of
it can be found in museums dotted around the area.
But rows of detached and affluent-looking houses in towns such as Sedgley
and Upper Gornal are an indication that this area has one of the highest
levels of owner-occupation in the country. Local unemployment is down to 8
per cent from 22 per cent in 1992. According to Tory statistics, 71 per cent
of local business leaders expect turnover to rise in the next 12 months.
A Conservative Central Office official working on the party's campaign said:
'It's not all that different from fighting Guildford or Chingford. It's very
much C2 territory - without the Essex accent.'
Mr Postles is confident the constituency is, at last, enjoying the promised
economic upturn. And he can certainly count on the support of a few
hard-core Conservatives.
'This isn't Christchurch or Eastleigh,' he says. 'In the Black Country
people are steeped in local tradition, they care about local issues and they
like stability.'
There are signs of that. Mr John Guest, a retired refuse collector, said:
'The government has its problems. But Tories here will stick with the
government through and through.'
Others say that the decline in regional unemployment is making itself felt.
Mr Roy Hampton, a gas engineer, said: 'I'll vote Tory again. You just need
to give the Tories time to let the economic changes make themselves felt,
that's all. People aren't being patient enough.'
But Labour's campaign is milking national discontent with the Tories to good
effect.
A mother-of-two in the Merry Hill shopping centre said: 'I voted Tory last
time but it will be Labour now. The Tories don't understand what the tax
rises have done to families like ours.'
A pensioner who is also thinking of switching said: 'I'm impressed with Tony
Blair. He appears sensible in a way Labour didn't before.'
Mr Fraser Kemp, who is masterminding Labour's campaign to take the seat,
refuses to get too excited about his party's chances. 'We cannot just assume
that the Tories are losing voters,' he said this week. 'We need to go out
and win them over.'
If the government loses this seat, its position at Westminster will be even
worse. But the parliamentary arithmetic is not the main issue. A Labour win
here would show that Mr Tony Blair's party can attract voters who have never
thought of supporting it before. That could signal a vital turning-point in
its fortunes.
</TEXT>
<XX>
