<HEADLINE>
FT  09 DEC 94 / Lloyd's reporting change delayed
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RALPH ATKINS, Insurance Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Lloyd's of London has postponed plans for ending its three-year accounting
system after discovering that the change requires European Union rules to be
modified.
Mr David Rowland, Lloyd's chairman, said the setback was 'frustrating'. For
new corporate members, allowed to invest in the insurance market for the
first time this year, the move means 1994 profits are likely to published in
1997, not 1996 as expected.
Lloyd's regards the three-year accounting system as outdated, with the
insurance market becoming more dependent on investment from companies rather
than Names - individual's whose assets have traditionally supported it.
It hoped to move to a two-year accounting period next year when it was
planning to report results for both 1992 and 1993. That would have meant
expected losses in 1992 being reported with figures showing the market
returning to profitability in 1993.
Lloyd's said yesterday that when the plans were unveiled in September legal
opinion was divided over whether references to the market in the EU
insurance accounts directive would require modification.
It said: 'It is now clear that the text will have to be changed and the
Department of Trade and Industry has advised that this may take up to two
years or possibly longer.'
</TEXT>
