<HEADLINE>
FT  09 DEC 94 / Power generators warned on plant disposals
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Professor Stephen Littlechild, the electricity regulator, yesterday showed
impatience with the two main generators over plant disposals and said he was
considering regulatory changes to allow regional power companies to buy
plant from them.
Prof Littlechild said neither National Power nor PowerGen had submitted
proposals which would meet the objectives of an undertaking to try to sell
off 5,000MW to 6,000MW of capacity to increase competition.
He said he had told the generators that 'arrangements which left either
company with a continuing involvement in or significant influence on the
commercial operation of the plant would not resolve the underlying
competition issues'.
He added: 'I have asked both parties to explore a range of alternatives.'
The generators have until the end of next year to try to sell the plant, but
Prof Littlechild is believed to be concerned about their lack of progress to
meeting the commitment.
His statement comes a month before the government publishes the prospectus
for the sale of its remaining 40 per cent stakes in National Power and
PowerGen. The potential problems arising from the plant disposal commitments
are a concern for investors.
Prof Littlechild has previously warned that he will refer the matter to the
Monopolies and Mergers Commission if he is not satisfied with the outcome.
Writing in a consultation document, Prof Littlechild said several regional
electricity companies had asked about the possibility of relaxing limits on
generating their own electricity needs. The limit is about 15 per cent.
Some companies want it lifted to allow them to bid, either alone or as part
of consortia, for the National Power and PowerGen plant. Eastern Group and
Southern Electric are thought to be among them.
The prospect of regional electricity companies buying more electricity from
their own subsidiaries raises monopoly questions, however.
Prof Littlechild said even after 1998, when full competition is planned for
power supply, the companies 'would be likely to retain a significant degree
of de facto market power for a period'. He added: 'Where such market power
exists, a (company) which is purchasing electricity from a power station in
which it is a shareholder may face a potential conflict of interest.'
The regulator is suggesting a system under which regional electricity
companies would be prohibited or restricted from buying hedging contracts
from power stations in which they had an interest.
This, he says, could allow a company to 'contribute more fully to the
development of competition in generation without the allegation that it was
exploiting its captive market and local monopoly position'.
</TEXT>
