<HEADLINE>
FT  09 DEC 94 / Battle over Ulster fraud stepped up: Renewed fears on
racketeering
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JIMMY BURNS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Government officials have drawn up proposals to combat financial crime in
Northern Ireland, in the expectation that some former paramilitaries may
continue racketeering even if a lasting peace is achieved.
Some senior security officials believe that a number of former
paramilitaries will continue to engage in fraud and extortion, either in
their own right or in organised criminal groups. They consider that
investment generated by the 'peace dividend' may present opportunities for
financial crime and are insisting that any significant investment from the
US and the European Union be closely controlled by civil servants.
They fear that current legislation may not be adequate in the changing
political circumstances. Under the Northern Ireland Emergency Powers Act the
security forces act against racketeering and extortion on the basis of
evidence that these are contributing to paramilitary organisations.
The Northern Ireland Office's terrorist finance unit, which has co-ordinated
a secret war against IRA fundraising for four years, is considering options
based on legislation against organised crime in Italy and the US.
The recent armed raid on a Newry post office, in which IRA members acting
under orders from their local commander killed one man and stole Pounds
150,000, highlights how entangled terrorism and financial crime have become.
It is understood that the IRA leadership has privately indicated to Irish
officials that the money from the raid could be returned as a sign that
armed robberies have been discontinued to mark the organisation's commitment
to the peace process. But some IRA members who are less supportive of the
ceasefire process are concerned that the organisation is being financially
weakened.
The IRA's 'operational requirements' just before the ceasefire are thought
to have been running at about Pounds 3m a year, half the figure estimated in
the early 1990s.
It is thought that it is now using its funds for intelligence gathering and
to support members who remain fugitives from justice as well as families of
political prisoners. There is little evidence of big arms purchases.
The government claims success in cracking down on one of the main sources of
fund-raising for the IRA in recent years by closing numerous Belfast
drinking clubs associated with the paramilitaries and reopening them under
strict licences.
The NIO's finance unit claims to have found no evidence of companies being
used as IRA fronts, although such companies are widely believed to exist.
Officials remain anxious to control another traditional source of IRA
funding - from Irish-American supporters.
Mr Gerry Adams, the Sinn Fein president, announced plans in Washington this
week for Cairde Sinn Fein, a new fundraising organisation in the US on
behalf of the IRA's political arm. He pledged 'accountability and
transparency'.
Mr Adams is aware that Noraid, an organisation once stigmatised as the IRA's
main fundraising arm in the US, has openly defied a court order to file
regular reports with the US Justice Department.
The organisation's last filed accounts cover the 12 months to July 1991 and
involve claimed funds of Dollars 1.8m.
According to Department of Justice officials the last Northern Ireland group
to register a fundraising organisation was Mr John Hume's Social Democratic
and Labour party in March this year.
British officials have long suspected that funds raised on behalf of
republican prisoners in the US were being diverted to the IRA.
</TEXT>
