<HEADLINE>
FT  09 DEC 94 / Sinn Fein names its Stormont delegation
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JIMMY BURNS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Two leading republicans who were instrumental in persuading the IRA to
commit itself politically to the peace process lead the Sinn Fein delegation
attending today's talks with government officials at the former parliament
buildings in Stormont Castle.
Mr Martin McGuinness, the deputy leader of Sinn Fein, and Mr Gerry Kelly
have both served terrorist-related prison sentences. Mr McGuinness, an IRA
commander in Derry in the 1970s, was convicted in the Republic of Ireland
for being a member of the IRA. Mr Kelly was imprisoned for his part in an
IRA bombing campaign in Northern Ireland.
Although officially leading members of Sinn Fein, both retain strong links
with the IRA leadership.
In the past 18 months they have been involved as members of Sinn Fein in
secret contacts with both the Irish and British governments, preparing the
ground for the declaration of the IRA ceasefire at the end of August this
year.
The role of Mr McGuinness in tomorrow's talks - in the eyes of civil
servants - will be as a broker between the republican movement's politicians
and its hardline men-at-arms.
Mr Kelly, an active republican from the Belfast area, was involved in a mass
break-out from the Maze prison in 1983, and arrested three years later in
the Netherlands. He was extradited to the UK where he served the remainder
of a prison sentence related to terrorist offences.
The Sinn Fein delegation was selected after a period of intense discussions
in the republican movement, and in consultation with the IRA, where there is
some unease at the continuance of the ceasefire.
The delegation aims to be broadly representative of republican opinion.
Delegates have been drawn from a wide geographical area and there is a
strong presence of women.
Among the leading delegates is Ms Lucilita Breathnach, general secretary of
Sinn Fein since 1989. A polyglot, she is thought to be closely involved with
developing international contacts on behalf of the party.
Another is Ms Siobhan O'Hanlon, a member of the party's northern executive,
who works closely with Mr Gerry Adams, the party's president, and will
report to him.
Mr Adams and other leading republicans plan to become involved in direct
talks with the British government early next year.
The fifth member of the Sinn Fein delegation is Mr Sean McManus, a former
chairman of Sinn Fein and a member of the party's national executive. He is
a district councillor in County Sligo, in the Republic of Ireland.
A sixth member of Sinn Fein is expected to attend to take notes.
</TEXT>
