FT  09 DEC 94 / Accounts partner quits over probe
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JIM KELLY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A partner with a London-based firm of accountants has left the business
following a probe into apparent financial irregularities, Jim Kelly writes.
Mr John Goldring, a partner with Casson Beckman, is well known in the music
industry, where many of his clients work. It is understood that the apparent
irregularities involve about Pounds 2m.
The executive chairman of Casson Beckman, Mr Geoff Barnes, said: 'We are all
extremely shocked at the circumstances which have led to the departure of
John Goldring. I have taken personal charge of this matter and will head the
dedicated special team which will continue to work hard and do everything it
can to resolve this matter as soon as possible.'
In a statement issued last night the firm said the departure had 'resulted
from on-going investigations carried out by the executive board and their
advisers into certain apparent financial irregularities concerning funds
over which John Goldring had control by virtue of personal appointments he
held in relation to certain clients'.
It added: 'As soon as Casson Beckman became aware of these matters a special
team was set up to investigate the full extent of these apparent
irregularities and the few affected clients have been contacted personally.
'The Institute of Chartered Accountants in England and Wales has been
informed.'
Mr Goldring's lawyers, Jay Benning Levine &amp; Peltz, said that no statement
would be made on the matter.
