FT  09 DEC 94 / Guardian journalist quits after KGB links alleged
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A senior journalist on The Guardian newspaper, Mr Richard Gott, last night
resigned after The Spectator magazine accused him of once having close links
with the KGB.
In a resignation letter Mr Gott, a well known leftwing journalist and the
newspaper's literary editor, denied allegations in the right-of-centre
magazine that he had accepted money.
Mr Gott, best known for his coverage of Latin America, admitted however that
the Russians had paid for trips to Vienna, Athens and Nicosia to meet Soviet
representatives in the 1980s. The trips were apparently known to MI6.
In a letter printed in today's Guardian Mr Peter Preston, the paper's
editor, wrote that he accepted Mr Gott's resignation 'with the heaviest of
hearts' and said he hoped his distinctive voice would still be heard in the
paper in the future.
But of the trips Mr Preston said: 'I should have known. I should have been
told. You have resigned from the staff. That is accepted.'
The Spectator has used the information on Mr Gott for a broad attack on The
Guardian, set clearly in the context of the paper's coverage of unorthodox
behaviour by MPs. The front of this week's issue is dominated by part of a
Guardian front page on Mr Jonathan Aitken and the affair of the bill from
the Ritz hotel in Paris.
The Spectator also alleges that Mr Gott is only one of a list of British
citizens, some still in positions of authority, who are known by British
intelligence to have had connections with the KGB.
</TEXT>
