<HEADLINE>
FT  09 DEC 94 / Rule on pensions solvency diluted
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NORMA COHEN, Investments Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The government yesterday confirmed that the UK's biggest occupational
pension schemes will have to meet a significantly weaker minimum solvency
requirement than was initially proposed, when new pensions legislation is
introduced next week.
Mr Peter Lilley, social security secretary, announced details of some of the
thorniest issues raised by the legislation in response to a parliamentary
question.
The government has been under heavy pressure from employers' groups to ease
a solvency requirement that many feared would force them to sell equities -
which have historically offered higher returns - from their pension funds
and buy gilts, which have lower, though more predictable, total returns.
They said such a requirement could have forced employers to put more cash
into their schemes.
Details of the government's plans to significantly weaken some elements of
proposals contained in a June white paper have been circulating in the
pensions industry for several weeks.
Mr Lilley said schemes with assets of Pounds 100m or more would be allowed
to hold equities in respect of about 25 per cent of their current pension
liabilities. At present, the actuarial profession considers it imprudent to
hold assets other than gilts against pension liabilities.
Also, employers with schemes falling short of the minimum solvency
requirement will have more time than originally planned to make up the
shortfall.
Schemes with assets covering less than 90 per cent of liabilities will have
a year to make up the shortfall, instead of three months as planned. Schemes
with between 90 per cent and 100 per cent cover will have up to five years
to regain full solvency.
Mr Lilley also outlined how new age-related rebates on national insurance
contributions will work.
Currently there is a flat-rate rebate for all those contracting out of the
state earnings related pension scheme through personal pensions and
occupational money purchase schemes, giving much more generous tax breaks to
young people but encouraging them to opt back into Serps as they age.
Mr Lilley said that because the provision of age-related rebates for those
currently nearing retirement age would be very expensive, the rebate would
be limited to 9 per cent of relevant earnings.
</TEXT>
