<HEADLINE>
FT  09 DEC 94 / Germans may rethink Thorp deal
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
German electricity companies were yesterday considering formal proposals
from BNFL, the UK reprocessing company, which will give them the option of
taking back up to 1,400 tonnes of spent nuclear fuel they are due to start
sending to the UK next year.
Under the terms of a Pounds 900m contract BNFL is not due to start
reprocessing the fuel until 2005. The contract, drawn up in 1989, makes no
mention of what would happen if the Germans wanted the fuel back unprocessed
before then.
Although the German companies intend to go ahead with reprocessing, they are
concerned that political pressures will force a rethink.
Environmentalists - a strong political lobby in Germany - are concerned
about reprocessing in the UK since the terms of the contract require the
German companies to take back the plutonium and waste material after
reprocessing.
The issue has been under discussion between BNFL and the utilities since
October. The Germans have been engaged in similar discussions with Cogema,
the French reprocessing company which has a contract to take other spent
fuel.
BNFL was yesterday unable to disclose the details of its proposals, which it
sent to Germany earlier this week. It is thought, however, that it will
agree to sending back spent fuel unreprocessed if requested, providing the
Germans agree a substantial cancellation fee.
BNFL will want compensation for the costs of transporting the spent fuel to
the UK, of storing it and of conditioning it for transportation back to
Germany.
The contract is the second negotiated between BNFL and the German utilities.
Spent fuel in the first contract is already being reprocessed.
It forms part of the 'base load' of fuel which is being reprocessed in the
first 10 years of Thorp's existence. BNFL says the base load, which includes
spent fuel from Japan and the UK, will pay for the building and
decommissioning of the Pounds 2.8bn plant and provide a Pounds 500m profit.
This is disputed by environmentalists. Thorp has been the subject of
considerable con-troversy for more than a decade.
</TEXT>
