<HEADLINE>
FT  09 DEC 94 / Further rates rise warning by Bank
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER NORMAN, Economics Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Eddie George, the governor of the Bank of England, yesterday indicated
that further interest rate rises might be necessary to control inflation,
although he said he hoped rates would plateau 'fairly soon'.
The governor said it was too early to say whether Wednesday's half
percentage point increase in bank base rates to 6.25 per cent was enough to
curb inflation and whether the interest rate plateau would be established at
that level or higher. But because the authorities had acted early, the
interest rate peak would be lower than before.
Mr George said in evidence to the Commons Treasury and civil service
committee that he had initiated Wednesday's base rate rise. He recommended a
rise to the chancellor because of above-trend growth in the economy and
growing inflationary pressures.
He said: 'From my point of view, politics were irrelevant.' He conceded that
the government's Tuesday night defeat over value added tax on domestic fuel
might have influenced the readiness of Mr Kenneth Clarke, the chancellor, to
agree to the rate increase.
Mr George said that he asked the chancellor's office, before Tuesday's vote,
for Wednesday's meeting to be brought forward to 8.45am from the 9.30 time
originally scheduled.
This was a 'contingency' measure. The governor knew he would advise a rate
rise and, in the event of the chancellor agreeing, he wanted time to inform
the financial markets before that day's gilts auction.
The chancellor's office returned his call after the vote and agreed the new
time for the meeting.
Mr George pushed aside suggestions that the rate increase was politically
motivated. He said the bank had come close to recommending a rate increase a
month earlier at the November meeting between governor and chancellor. Mr
Clarke did not refer to the vote against the government in the meeting on
Wednesday, he added.
The governor firmly rejected any suggestion that the minutes of his monthly
meetings with the chancellor were doctored.
Mr George added his voice to a warning given earlier this week by Mr Alan
Budd, the government's chief economic adviser, about the risks of future tax
cuts.
These, he said, could be justified only if the productive growth of the
economy increased. Inappropriate tax cuts that encouraged inflation would
lead to higher interest rates, he said.
</TEXT>
