<HEADLINE>
FT  09 DEC 94 / World Trade News: All-Americas free trade zone 'by 2006'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GEORGE GRAHAM and STEPHEN FIDLER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MIAMI
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Leaders of 34 countries in the western hemisphere are expected to agree
plans to create a free trade area from Alaska to Cape Horn by 2006 during
the three-day Americas summit which starts today in Miami.
Just a week ago it seemed likely that no date would be set for completing
negotiations on setting up the free trade zone, but, barring any last-minute
veto when the leaders discuss trade tomorrow morning, a 2005 deadline for
agreement will be included in the summit declaration on Sunday.
A draft summit declaration calls for 'the conclusion of negotiations on the
Americas Free Trade Area no later than the year 2005' and for 'concrete
progress towards attainment of this objective by the end of this century'.
President Carlos Menem of Argentina said yesterday the next 12 years would
see further hemispheric summits to follow up the decisions made in Miami so
that a free trade zone came into effect by 2006.
US officials said the summit would lay down a schedule of official and
ministerial meetings to begin work immediately on the progressive
elimination of barriers to trade and investment, as well as a substantial
work programme for the Organisation of American States and the
Inter-American Development Bank.
The draft declaration says that free trade and greater economic integration
are key factors in raising living standards, improving working conditions
and protecting the environment.
While some countries had been reluctant to pin down a year, others, led by
Argentina, argued that it would be a severe setback if the Americas summit
were unable to agree on a date, when leaders of the Asia Pacific Economic
Co-operation forum last month had accepted a target date of 2020 for
establishing a free trade zone in the Pacific.
Argentina wanted the Americas Free Trade Area to be established by 2001, but
other countries, such as Mexico and Brazil, had resisted such an ambitious
target. Mr Menem said the best way to hemispheric integration was initially
to cement regional trade groupings, such as Mercosur - which groups
Argentina with Brazil, Paraguay and Uruguay. However, progress towards the
final goal depended on the speed with which the North American Free Trade
Agreement could be extended - and that largely hung on the disposition of
the US Congress.
The declaration of an Americas Free Trade Area is expected to be accompanied
by the announcement that Chile will be invited to begin negotiations early
next year on joining the US, Canada and Mexico in the North American Free
Trade Agreement.
Mr Lloyd Bentsen, the US Treasury secretary, said: 'I think we have to take
a lead. If we don't work with our hemispheric partners in building this
relationship on trade with the Americas, then we're going to find that the
Japanese and the Europeans are going to work to be their partners.'
The Miami summit is the first western hemisphere summit to be hosted by the
US - something that would have been difficult in earlier decades when the US
was viewed as a domineering imperial power by many Latin American countries.
Unlike previous regional summits in Panama in 1956 and in Uruguay in 1967,
this summit will be attended only by popularly elected leaders. The only
country not to be invited is Cuba.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>XBZ  North America.
    XDZ  Central America.
    XCZ  Latin America.
</CN>
