<HEADLINE>
FT  09 DEC 94 / Crisis in Orange County rebounds on bond market
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TONY JACKSON and GRAHAM BOWLEY
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK, LONDON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Arthur Levitt, chairman of the US Securities and Exchange Commission,
said yesterday the financial crisis in Orange County, California, was
'significant' for investors and the market, and conceded that better
disclosure might have brought it to light sooner.
Fears the county may be forced to liquidate its Dollars 20bn (Pounds 12.8bn)
fund portfolio have caused sharp widening of credit spreads in US domestic
and Eurodollar bond markets.
Orange County filed for bankruptcy on Tuesday after being hit by a loss of
Dollars 1.5bn from dealings in the bond market. This has fuelled speculation
that it will be forced to sell much of its Dollars 7.5bn portfolio of bonds,
triggering a flood on to the world's markets and suppressing prices.
These fears sent spreads - the difference in the yield on agency and
corporate bonds and that on US Treasury bonds - significantly wider as the
price of US corporate and agency bonds fell relative to the higher credit
rated US Treasury bonds.
The widening was initially more pronounced in the US domestic market but the
nervousness spread to the Eurobond market yesterday, where spreads widened
by about 5 to 10 basis points.
Orange County's portfolio consists mainly of municipal and agency bonds, and
the spreads on these instruments were hit hardest. 'There was a flight to
quality and this put pressure on spreads,' said one bond trader in London.
The market was also unnerved by rumours that other municipal funds might be
concealing huge losses.
San Diego County, also in California, said it had paper losses of Dollars
357m on a fund worth Dollars 3.3bn, largely because of its holdings of
derivatives. Mr Paul Boland, county treasurer, was quoted as dismissing
comparisons with Orange County, saying his fund was not leveraged and had no
liquidity problems.
Mr Levitt said the SEC had been monitoring Orange County before the crisis
erupted there, and was watching other unspecified investment pools across
the country. 'I would hope the balanced, calm approach to Orange County on
the part of all participants will continue,' he said.
</TEXT>
