FT  09 DEC 94 / Belgian defence minister quits
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By AP
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BRUSSELS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The Belgian defence minister, Mr Leo Delcroix, resigned yesterday after he
was implicated in a real estate scandal, the fourth senior government member
to be forced out this year. Mr Delcroix said he stepped down to keep the
government from becoming implicated in the scandal. Prime minister Jean-Luc
Dehaene announced that another Dutch-speaking Christian Democrat, Mr Karel
Pinxten, would become the new defence minister. Mr Delcroix had denied
earlier this year that he owned a villa in Provence, southern France, but he
admitted on Wednesday that he did, adding that the house was valued at
FFr15m (Pounds 1.78m) to FFr20m. But he denied that the villa was built with
illegal funds and illegal labour, as some allegations had claimed. In
January, deputy prime minister Guy Coeme, Mr Delcroix's predecessor at the
defence ministry, the minister-president of the Walloon regional government,
Mr Guy Spitaels, and his interior minister, Mr Guy Mathot, resigned after
their parliamentary immunity was lifted to investigate corruption
allegations. The three French-speaking Socialists denied any wrongdoing.
