<HEADLINE>
FT  09 DEC 94 / Leaders and laggards in internal market
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By EMMA TUCKER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BRUSSELS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Greece and Germany are trailing far behind other EU states in adopting
legislation crucial for the free flow of goods, services and capital across
the Union, and have contributed to a disappointing year for the internal
market.
Delivering its twice yearly roundup of delays to completion of the single
market, the European Commission said yesterday that a lack of political
commitment by member states had slowed progress.
On the eve of the single market's second anniversary, Mr Raniero Vanni
D'Archirafi, the commissioner responsible for the single market, told EU
ministers that developments had been most disappointing in intellectual and
industrial property, public procurement and insurance.
League tables compiled by the Commission show that Greece, which has only
implemented 77.9 per cent of the single market legislation, is the worst
offender by a long way. Of a total of 217 measures, it has made no progress
on 43. This compares with Denmark - the champion - which has only eight
outstanding.
The second slowest country is Germany which has made no progress on 26
directives, followed by Ireland with 24. France is the second most
efficient, followed by Britain, which has still not adopted 14 bits of
legislation.
On average, 89 per cent of the legislation necessary to ensure the free flow
of goods, services and capital has been adopted. But with some states
trailing badly, and progress differing markedly across sectors, Mr Vanni
D'Archirafi, stressed that much work remained to be done.
It was not enough for states merely to adopt the legislation on to their
national statute books. They had to ensure that national laws were of the
right quality, and corresponded to the requirements of EU legislation.
Brussels also accused member states of failing to respect the principle of
mutual recognition, whereby they recognise each other's standards for goods
and services where no harmonisation legislation is deemed necessary.
Mr Vanni D'Archirafi said the Commission had investigated 4,112 cases - half
of which concerned the single market - where it suspected that member states
were not respecting EU legislation. Of these, a majority were in France and
Germany.
Member states now look certain to back a Commission initiative that will
require them to inform Brussels every time any one of them intends to ban or
refuse entry for a product which has been lawfully produced in another
member state.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>BEZ  Belgium, EC.
    QRZ  European Economic Community (EC).
    GRZ  Greece, EC.
    DEZ  Germany, EC.
</CN>
