<HEADLINE>
FT  09 DEC 94 / Warburg and Morgan Stanley seek merger
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN GAPPER, Banking Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SG Warburg, the largest UK investment bank, announced yesterday that it
intended to give up its independence by merging with the US investment bank
Morgan Stanley in an effort to create a stronger global bank.
The announcement, prompted by widespread rumours in the London stock market
which drove up Warburg's share price, followed three months of talks on what
would be the most significant transatlantic merger the industry has seen.
The investment banks said their businesses were 'uniquely complementary,'
although the merger is expected to lead to cuts among Warburg's 4,472 staff
and Morgan Stanley's 9,300 staff as they eliminate duplication. Investment
banks have suffered from weakness and volatility in financial markets this
year, and both Warburg and Morgan Stanley have recently announced sharp
falls in profits.
Warburg has had difficulty fulfilling its aim to rival the large US
investment banks such as Goldman Sachs as a global player because of a
relatively small capital base and difficulty in penetrating US capital
markets.
Morgan Stanley is thought to view the merger as a means of making a stronger
impact in Asia and Europe. The bank has been expanding its staff recently,
partly to rebuild its position in the underwriting of stocks and bonds in
the US.
Large investment banks in Europe and the US increasingly believe they must
have a strong presence in many regions to gain business from cross-border
capital flows. This has led US banks to push strongly into Europe.
Heads of other UK investment banks said they thought the merger could create
a strong combined force, but it would face merger difficulties.
The banks said yesterday that they were 'discussing the possibility of
combining their businesses' by forming a new holding company. The company
will probably offer shares in exchange for existing Warburg and Morgan
Stanley equity.
The intended merger could be disrupted by a counter bid from another
institution. However, executives of both banks believe it would be hard to
mount a hostile bid, because much of the value of Warburg is in the
expertise of employees.
There is some uncertainty over Mercury Asset Management, the fund management
business 75 per cent owned by Warburg. The merged banks could be forced by
the Takeover Panel to offer to buy out minority shareholders.
The London Stock Exchange, which is trying to crack down on insider dealing,
contacted Warburg yesterday morning after a rise in its shares on rumours of
bids by JP Morgan, the US investment bank, and HSBC Holdings, the UK bank.
Its intervention forced Warburg to announce - a week ahead of schedule - the
merger talks with Morgan Stanley.
In London, Warburg's shares closed 119p up at 791p yesterday, after reaching
a high of 830p. In New York, Morgan Stanley shares closed down Dollars 1 5/8
at Dollars 55 1/4.
Editorial Comment and Observer, Page 17; Lex, Page 18; Reaction and
analysis, Page 20; London stocks, Page 40
