<HEADLINE>
FT  09 DEC 94 / Clarke bridges Pounds 1bn gap with extra tax package:
Further duties on petrol, tobacco and alcohol after government's VAT defeat
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER NORMAN and PHILIP STEPHENS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Kenneth Clarke, the chancellor, yesterday turned to smokers, motorists
and drinkers to plug the gap in the government finances caused by this
week's Commons defeat over value added tax on domestic fuel.
Addressing a packed House of Commons, a boisterous chancellor announced a 1p
per litre increase in petrol and diesel taxes and increases of about 4 per
cent in tobacco and alcohol duties from January 1 to make up for Pounds 1bn
of revenue lost next year.
He said the government would trim the social security compensation package
that was to protect pensioners and others on income related benefits from
the aborted plan to increase VAT on fuel to 17.5 per cent. Mr Clarke also
signalled further cuts of Pounds 300m a year in public spending from 1996-97
onwards to make up further revenue shortfalls.
Mr Clarke told the Commons that holding the rate of VAT on domestic fuel at
8 per cent would reduce revenue by about Pounds 1bn in 1995-96 and Pounds
1.5bn in subsequent years. He ostentatiously rejected cutting spending plans
for the coming financial year or levying more direct taxes on individuals or
imposing new taxes on businesses.
In a mini-Budget reminiscent of austerity Budgets in the 1950s, he chose to
raise Pounds 780m from higher excise duties on fuel, tobacco and alcohol.
The social security measures would save Pounds 190m in 1995-96 and more in
following years. A reduction in pension rates meant that national insurance
contributions would start on earnings of Pounds 58 a week, rather than
Pounds 59, from next April, raising receipts by Pounds 50m.
Mr Clarke's pugnacious performance in the Commons drew loud applause from
Tory MPs and raised hopes among ministers that the wounds in the
Conservative party inflicted by the VAT defeat would now begin to heal.
But the chancellor's colleagues were under no illusions that the increases
in duties will be popular. With many Conservatives already under pressure
from the brewing and off-licence industries regarding cheaper wine and beer
imports from France, the rise in alcohol duties attracted criticism from
several Tory MPs.
The package was given a rude reception by the Brewers' and Licensed
Retailers' Association: 'It is economic lunacy, French brewers and retailers
will be laughing their way to the bank.'
There was disquiet on the right of the Tory party that Mr Clarke had
confined cuts in public spending to the second and third years of the
expenditure programme. Some cabinet members were said to have made clear
that they would have preferred deeper cuts in spending totals.
But the chancellor was dismissive of criticism of his performance during the
past two weeks from the right of his party. He told journalists at a press
conference: 'I don't think the entire right is out to get me. One or two I
wouldn't be surprised. I feel the same about them.' He accused some of the
Eurosceptics of spreading 'malicious fiction'.
The chancellor admitted yesterday's plans were very much 'second choice
measures' involving 'serious snags' that he would have liked to have
avoided.
The increased road fuel duties would affect the rural motorist. The decision
to increase drink duties rather than to freeze them would affect distillers,
brewers and the licensed trade. He said he did not like putting up tobacco
duties because of large-scale smuggling, and for this reason left the tax on
hand-rolling tobacco unchanged.
But he insisted that the government was 'committed to taking all the
necessary measures to put the public finances on a sound footing' to keep
Britain's 'healthy recovery on track'.
Mr Clarke's new plans will put 1p on a pint of beer, 5p on a standard bottle
of wine and 26p on a bottle of sprits. They will add 6p to a packet of 20
cigarettes.
Trimming the social security compensation would mean a single state pension
in the next financial year would be 30p a week lower than announced last
week and that for couples 35p lower.
Industry groups, such as the Confederation of British Industry and British
Chambers of Commerce, critical of Wednesday's interest rate rise, were
relieved that business had escaped punishment. Financial markets were
unmoved by the chancellor's package.
With Labour claiming that the latest measures add a further Pounds 29 a year
to the tax bills of the average family, ministers are expecting a crushing
defeat in next week's Dudley by-election.
Mr Gordon Brown, Labour party shadow chancellor, said the net cut in the
average family's income as a result of all Budgets since the general
election would reach Pounds 800 a year by next April.
Budget statement and reaction, Pages 10 and 11; Editorial Comment, Page 17;
Lex, Page 18; Bonds, Page 28; Currencies, Page 30; London stocks, Page 40
</TEXT>
