<HEADLINE>
FT  08 DEC 94 / UK Company News: Chairman retires with BTP ahead at Pounds
18.1m
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID WIGHTON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BTP, the speciality chemicals group, reported a 39 per cent rise in interim
pre-tax profits from Pounds 13m to Pounds 18.1m as it announced the
retirement of chairman Mr Frank Buckley after 27 years with the company.
Mr Buckley steps down at a time when the group is riding high following last
year's Pounds 107m acquisition of most of MTM's assets. On the back of the
deal BTP's earnings per share rose from 7.04p to 9p in the six months to
September 30, on turnover 23 per cent higher at Pounds 161m, compared with
Pounds 131m last time.
Mr Stephen Hannam, who moves up from managing director to chief executive,
said there was more to come. 'What we got was a fantastic set of assets
which will be the base for organic growth for many years,' he said.
Along with other speciality chemicals companies BTP has seen a sharp
increase in raw material costs over the last few months. But Mr Hannam said
it would be pushing through price rises ranging from '5 per cent to well
into double figures' next month and was confident that it would pas on all
its increased costs by the end of the financial year.
Demand in most of BTP's main markets is improving. Its adhesives and textile
coatings division, which was hardest hit by the recession, saw operating
profits recover to Pounds 3.43m (Pounds 2.79m) while performance chemicals
rose to Pounds 4.23m (Pounds 3.29m). Boosted by the MTM deal, biocides and
fine chemicals jumped to Pounds 8.62m (Pounds 4.43m), while the industrial
division held at Pounds 3.34m (Pounds 3.41m) after last year's strong
growth.
The dividend rises 8.7 per cent from 3.45p to 3.75p.
The shares firmed 1p to 283p, valuing the company at Pounds 382m. When Mr
Buckley, now 66, joined what was then British Tar Products in 1967 it was
valued at just Pounds 137,000.
Mr Buckley became chairman and chief executive in 1978 and dropped the chief
executive role only last year. He will receive Pounds 393,000 for the rest
of his two-year rolling contract and has been invited to become honorary
president.
The new non-executive chairman is Mr John Ketteley, 55, who has been
non-executive deputy chairman since 1979.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Companies:-
</XX>
<CO>BTP.
</CO>
<XX>
