<HEADLINE>
FT  08 DEC 94 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MARTIN HOYLE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
As with some momentous state occasion, BBC2 has changed its schedules at the
last moment to accommodate the Royal Opera's new production of La traviata
from Covent Garden. This is the collaboration between Sir Georg Solti and
the National Theatre's Richard Eyre. On the first night the reception was
ecstatic. Why? The conductor was precise, energetic and unfeeling. The
director had patently never worked in opera before, had nothing to offer in
the way of characterisation or interpretation, and was uncertain what to do
with the chorus. The leading soprano is young, pretty and mellifluous, but
barely scratches the surface of Verdi's moving vision of the lady of the
camellias; yet the audience reacted as if she were a combination of Maria
Callas, Mother Teresa and Samantha Fox. It may be better on the box, and you
can watch programmes in those interminable intervals (they're just as long
in the Opera House). At least it makes a change from those obsessive relays
from the New York Met, another of the BBC's little mysteries.
</TEXT>
